### Adding Additional Strategies

To add additional [passport.js](http://passportjs.org) strategies, pass it to the middleware's `options`:

```json
{
    "middleware": {
        "auth": {
            "enabled": true,
            "priority": 113,
            "module": {
                "name": "auth-paypal",
                "arguments": [{
                    "strategies": {
                       "custom": "require:mycustomstrategy"
                    },
                   "accessTokenLogin": true
                }]
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Or with arguments as:

```json
{
    "middleware": {
        "auth": {
            "enabled": true,
            "priority": 113,
            "module": {
                "name": "auth-paypal",
                "arguments": [{
                    "strategies": {
                       "custom": {
                           "strategy": "require:mycustomstrategy",
                           "arguments": [ ...args ]
                       }
                    }
                }]
            }
        }
    }
}
```

The `custom` strategy can now be used by either:

```javascript
app.get('/somepath', auth.custom({ failureRedirect: '/someplace' }), function (req, res) {
    res.writeHead(200);
    res.end();
});
```

Or:

```javascript
app.get('/somepath', passport.authenticate('custom', { failureRedirect: '/someplace' }), function (req, res) {
    res.writeHead(200);
    res.end();
});
```

In the cases above, if the stategy has a internal name, then `custom` will still be used for the helper (i.e. `auth.custom`), but not when invoking passport directly.

Example:

```
app.get('/somepath', passport.authenticate('internal-name-for-custom', { failureRedirect: '/someplace' }), function (req, res) {
    res.writeHead(200);
    res.end();
});
```

